            {
                "@type": "Question",
                "name": "Can a Public Limited Company be converted into a Private Limited Company in India?",
                "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Yes. Section 14 of the Companies Act 2013 read with Rule 41 of the Companies (Incorporation) Rules 2014 provides the statutory pathway. The conversion requires a special resolution at the EGM, filing of Form MGT-14, newspaper publication of Form INC-25A, individual creditor and debenture holder notice in Form INC-26, application to the Regional Director in Form RD-1 and filing of the RD order with ROC in Form INC-28." }
            },
            {
                "@type": "Question",
                "name": "What is the procedure for converting Public Limited to Private Limited in 2026?",
                "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Pass a special resolution at the EGM (75 percent majority); file MGT-14 within 30 days; publish INC-25A newspaper advertisement in English and vernacular dailies plus individual INC-26 notices to creditors; observe 21-day objection window; file Form RD-1 with the Regional Director within 60 days; attend RD hearing if objections received; receive RD order; file INC-28 with ROC within 15 days. End-to-end 60 to 90 days for unlisted companies." }
            },
            {
                "@type": "Question",
                "name": "Why convert a Public Limited Company to a Private Limited Company?",
                "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Common reasons - the original public structure was adopted for an IPO plan that did not materialise; the company has contracted in scale and Public Limited compliance burden no longer justifies the structure; family-controlled or closely-held companies want tighter promoter control and restricted share transfers; post-acquisition simplification by a strategic buyer; reduction in cost audit, secretarial audit and AOC-4 XBRL compliance load." }
            },
            {
                "@type": "Question",
                "name": "How long does Public to Private Limited conversion take?",
                "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "For an unlisted Public Limited Company with no objections during the 21-day window, end-to-end timeline is 60 to 90 days. Listed Public Limited Companies require SEBI delisting under SEBI (Delisting of Equity Shares) Regulations 2021 as a precondition - this adds 6 to 12 months. Companies with member count above 200 need a pre-conversion buyback or share consolidation adding 2 to 4 months." }
            },
            {
                "@type": "Question",
                "name": "What is the role of the Regional Director in this conversion?",
                "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "The Regional Director is the deciding authority for Section 14 conversions. Originally exercised by the NCLT, the power was shifted to the Central Government by the Companies (Amendment) Act 2019 and delegated to the Regional Director through Notification SO 6225(E) dated 18 December 2018. The Regional Director examines the Form RD-1 application, scrutinises objections, holds hearings where needed and issues the order approving or rejecting the conversion." }
            },
            {
                "@type": "Question",
                "name": "What is the maximum number of members allowed in a Private Limited Company?",
                "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Section 2(68) of the Companies Act 2013 caps Private Limited Company membership at 200, excluding past and present employees who became members during their employment and continue to be members. If the Public Limited Company has more than 200 members, a pre-conversion member count reduction (typically buyback under Section 68 or consolidation) is required." }
            },
            {
                "@type": "Question",
                "name": "Do listed companies need to delist before converting to Private Limited?",
                "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Yes. Listed Public Limited Companies must complete SEBI delisting under SEBI (Delisting of Equity Shares) Regulations 2021 BEFORE initiating Section 14 conversion. The delisting can be through Reverse Book Building (for actively traded shares) or fixed price route (for smaller or thinly-traded shares). Only after the SEBI delisting order is final can the Companies Act 2013 conversion procedure begin." }
            },
            {
                "@type": "Question",
                "name": "What happens if creditors object during the 21-day window?",
                "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "If objections are received from creditors, debenture holders or members during the 21-day window post newspaper publication and individual notice service, the Regional Director schedules a hearing within 30 days. Patron's CS team attends the hearing at Lok Nayak Bhawan with documented responses to each objection. The RD records the hearing in an affidavit before issuing the final order - which may approve, reject or approve with conditions." }
            }
        ]
    }
    </script>
