<!-- SECTION 2: OVERVIEW / INTRO + TL;DR -->
<section class="content-section" id="overview-section">
    <div class="content-container">
        <div class="text-content">
            <h2 class="section-title">Public Ltd to Pvt Ltd Conversion in Delhi - Overview</h2>
            <div class="content-text">
                <div class="highlight-box" style="margin-bottom:20px;">
                    <p><strong>&#128204; TL;DR - Public to Pvt Ltd Conversion Services at a Glance</strong></p>
                    <p>A Public Limited Company can be converted to a Private Limited Company under Section 14 of the Companies Act 2013 read with Rule 41 of the Companies (Incorporation) Rules 2014. The conversion requires special resolution, Regional Director approval via Form RD-1, newspaper publication of Form INC-25A inviting objections and filing of the RD order in Form INC-28. Typical timeline is 60 to 90 days. Patron INR 49,999 fixed.</p>
                </div>
                <p><div class='table-responsive-wrapper'>
                <table>
                    <thead><tr><th>Quick Reference</th><th>Details</th></tr></thead>
                    <tbody>
                        <tr><td>Governing Laws</td><td>Companies Act 2013 - Section 13 (MOA), Section 14 (AOA - charging + proviso), Section 18 (body corporate continuity), Section 117 (resolution filing); Rule 41 Companies (Incorporation) Rules 2014 + SO 6225(E) dated 18 Dec 2018 delegating RD power post Companies (Amendment) Act 2019</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Applicable To</td><td>UNLISTED Public Limited Companies in Delhi with (a) members under 200 post-conversion, (b) no outstanding public deposits, (c) not under investigation, inspection or prosecution. Listed companies need SEBI delisting first.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Timeline</td><td>End-to-end 60 to 90 days (unlisted); 8 to 14 months (listed - includes SEBI delisting precondition)</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Cost (Patron)</td><td>INR 49,999 FIXED (Exl GST and Govt. Charges) - end-to-end including RD hearing representation</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Approval Authority</td><td>Regional Director (Northern Region), Lok Nayak Bhawan, Khan Market, New Delhi - delegated from Central Government</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Member Cap Post-Conversion</td><td>200 maximum (excluding past and present employees) under Section 2(68)</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Six Statutory Forms</td><td>MGT-14, INC-25A (newspaper), INC-26 (creditor notice), RD-1, INC-27 (integrated with RD-1), INC-28 (RD order filing)</td></tr>
                    </tbody>
                </table>
                </div></p>
                <p>A Public Limited Company status makes sense when it is needed - IPO planning, public capital raise, institutional fundraising at scale, ESOP across hundreds of employees. When the original rationale no longer holds (the IPO plan shelved, the institutional round moved to family or strategic instead, the operating scale modest enough that Public Limited compliance burden outweighs benefits), conversion back to Private Limited becomes the right answer. The procedural pathway is Section 14 of the Companies Act 2013 read with Rule 41 of the Companies (Incorporation) Rules 2014 - and the critical complication versus the reverse direction (Pvt to Public, which needs only MGT-14 plus INC-27) is that this conversion requires explicit Regional Director approval via Form RD-1, with mandatory newspaper publication of Form INC-25A inviting public objections, individual notice to all creditors and debenture holders, and a 21-day waiting period before the RD application can be processed.</p>
                <p>Content is reviewed quarterly for accuracy.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

<!-- SECTION 3: WHAT IS GSTAT APPEAL FILING -->
<section class="content-section" id="what-section">
    <div class="content-container">
        <div class="two-column">
            <div class="column-content">
                <h2 class="section-title">How Public Limited Becomes Private Limited Under Section 14</h2>
                <div class="content-text what-is-definition">
                    
                    <p>Conversion of a Public Limited Company to a Private Limited Company is the statutory process under which an existing company alters its Articles of Association under Section 14 of the Companies Act 2013, with corresponding amendments to the Memorandum under Section 13, such that the company's constitutional documents and name change to reflect Private Limited status. The legal characterisation under Section 18 is that the company continues as the same body corporate - assets, liabilities, contracts, pending legal proceedings and ongoing tax compliance carry forward unbroken; only the company type changes.</p>

<p>Section 14 of the Companies Act 2013 includes a critical proviso - "any alteration having the effect of conversion of a public company into a private company shall not be valid unless it is approved by an order of the Central Government". The Central Government's power was originally exercisable by the National Company Law Tribunal (NCLT); the Companies (Amendment) Act 2019 shifted the power to the Central Government, which delegated it to the Regional Director through Notification SO 6225(E) dated 18 December 2018. In practice this means the <strong>Regional Director (Northern Region) at Lok Nayak Bhawan, Khan Market is the deciding authority for Delhi-registered companies.</strong></p>

<p>The full procedure under Rule 41 of the Companies (Incorporation) Rules 2014 includes special resolution at a duly convened EGM, filing MGT-14 within 30 days, simultaneous newspaper publication of Form INC-25A in English and vernacular dailies inviting public objections, individual written notice to all creditors and debenture holders in Form INC-26, a 21-day objection window, filing Form RD-1 (with the integrated INC-27 conversion application) within 60 days of the special resolution, an RD hearing where objections are received, and finally filing the RD order with the ROC in Form INC-28 within 15 days of receipt. The ROC then issues a fresh Certificate of Incorporation with the new Private Limited name. Delhi anchors this engagement because both the Regional Director (Northern Region) and ROC NCT of Delhi and Haryana are physically located in Delhi - RD hearings, INC-28 follow-ups and newspaper publication coordination all happen here.</p>

                </div>
                <div class="highlight-box" style="margin-top:20px;">
                    <p><strong>Key Terms for Public to Pvt Ltd Conversion:</strong></p>
                    <p><strong>Section 14 Companies Act 2013:</strong> Charging section for alteration of Articles; contains the Central Government approval proviso for Public-to-Private conversion.</p>
<p><strong>Section 18 Companies Act 2013:</strong> Body corporate continuity preserved; assets, liabilities, contracts and proceedings carry forward.</p>
<p><strong>Section 2(68) Private Company:</strong> Restricts right to transfer shares; limits members to 200 (excluding past and present employees); prohibits invitation to public for subscription.</p>
<p><strong>Rule 41 Companies (Incorporation) Rules 2014:</strong> Procedural rules - special resolution, newspaper publication, individual creditor notice, 21-day waiting, RD-1, hearing, RD order, INC-28.</p>
<p><strong>Form MGT-14:</strong> Special resolution filing with ROC within 30 days of passing (Section 117).</p>
<p><strong>Form RD-1:</strong> Application to Regional Director within 60 days of special resolution.</p>
<p><strong>Form INC-25A:</strong> Newspaper advertisement format under Rule 41(2); English daily + vernacular daily; invites public objections.</p>
<p><strong>Form INC-26:</strong> Individual written notice to every creditor and debenture holder under Rule 41(3).</p>
<p><strong>Form INC-28:</strong> RD order filing with ROC within 15 days of receipt.</p>
<p><strong>Regional Director (Northern Region):</strong> Decision-maker at Lok Nayak Bhawan, Khan Market, New Delhi - for companies registered in Delhi, Haryana, Punjab, HP, J&K, Chandigarh, Ladakh.</p>
<p><strong>Companies (Amendment) Act 2019 + SO 6225(E):</strong> Shifted approval power from NCLT to Central Government; delegated to RD via SO 6225(E) dated 18 December 2018.</p>

                </div>
            </div>
