<!-- SECTION 4: WHO CAN FILE -->
<section class="content-section" id="who-section">
    <div class="content-container">
        <div class="text-content">
            <h2 class="section-title">Which Public Limited Companies Should Convert (and Which Cannot)</h2>
            <div class="content-text">
                
                <p>Conversion to Private Limited is HIGH-VALUE for the following Delhi-NCR Public Limited Company profiles:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Unlisted Public Ltd Companies with shelved IPO plans:</strong> The heavier compliance burden no longer justifies the structure when the original public-route fundraising plan did not materialise.</li>
                    <li><strong>Family-controlled or closely-held Public Ltd Companies:</strong> Fewer than 200 members in substance; promoter wants tighter control and lighter governance.</li>
                    <li><strong>Public Ltd Companies acquired by strategic buyers:</strong> Want simpler post-acquisition governance and tighter share-transfer restrictions.</li>
                    <li><strong>Public Ltd Companies whose business has materially contracted:</strong> Statutory audit thresholds, secretarial audit, cost audit, AOC-4 XBRL, MGT-7 and four-board-meetings-per-year load exceeds operational scale.</li>
                    <li><strong>Public Ltd Companies with member base already under 200:</strong> No realistic public fundraising plan in the next 3-5 years.</li>
                    <li><strong>Companies rolling out Sweat Equity or ESOPs to a tightly-held group:</strong> Private Limited's 200-member cap is rarely a real constraint at that scale.</li>
                </ul>
                <p style="margin-top:16px;"><strong>Conversion is NOT possible or NOT optimal for:</strong> LISTED Public Ltd Companies on BSE / NSE (must first complete SEBI delisting under SEBI Regulations 2021 - 6-12 month prerequisite); companies with members exceeding 200 under Section 2(68) - hard cap, requires pre-conversion buyback under Section 68 (2-4 month prerequisite); companies with outstanding public deposits (must first repay or discharge); companies under ongoing investigation, inspection or prosecution by SFIO, SEBI or any other authority (Rule 41(5) bar); subsidiaries of public companies (deemed public under Section 2(71) - parent's public status flows through); companies planning institutional Series C / D or IPO in the near term (procedural waste to convert and revert).</p>

            </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

