<!-- SECTION 9: CHALLENGES -->
<section class="content-section" id="challenges-section">
    <div class="content-container">
        <div class="text-content">
            <h2 class="section-title">Common Challenges and Patron Solutions</h2>
            <div class="content-text">
                <div class="table-responsive-wrapper">
                <table>
                    <thead><tr><th>Challenge</th><th>Impact</th><th>How Patron Accounting Solves It</th></tr></thead>
                    <tbody>
                        <tr><td>Members exceeding 200</td><td>The 200-member cap under Section 2(68) is hard and cannot be circumvented at the time of conversion - excluding past and present employees who became members during employment.</td><td>Patron plans a pre-conversion buyback under Section 68 of the Companies Act 2013 or a structured share transfer to consolidate ownership into fewer holders. This is a 2-4 month prerequisite. Where the excess is small and concentrated, board-driven buyback offers can quickly reduce member count.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Creditor objections to the conversion</td><td>Secured creditors may object if they perceive the change to private status as increasing their credit risk (reduced disclosure, restricted share transferability).</td><td>Patron obtains explicit NOC from all material secured creditors BEFORE the special resolution. Where NOC is refused, terms are renegotiated (additional security, covenant modifications) to convert the objection into consent. The RD hearing then becomes a formality rather than contested.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Pending litigation, investigation or prosecution</td><td>Rule 41(5) bars conversion if the company is under investigation, inspection or prosecution by SFIO, SEBI or any other authority. Concealed matters surface during RD scrutiny.</td><td>Patron runs a pre-conversion clearance check via written confirmation from the relevant Registrar, MCA Inspectorate, SFIO and SEBI where applicable. Where any matter is pending, resolve first or defer conversion. Concealed pending matters result in rejection with reputational cost.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Listed Public Limited Company status</td><td>Listed companies cannot directly convert; SEBI delisting under SEBI (Delisting of Equity Shares) Regulations 2021 is a precondition - typically a 6-12 month process.</td><td>For listed candidates, Patron maps the delisting strategy first - Reverse Book Building (RBB) for active listings versus fixed price for smaller or thinly-traded shares. SEBI delisting is sequenced; the Section 14 conversion begins only after the SEBI delisting order is final.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Regional Director scrutiny on the 'real reason'</td><td>The RD may probe whether the conversion is being used to avoid disclosure, restrict minority rights or facilitate a transaction.</td><td>Patron documents the genuine business rationale at engagement start - cost reduction, control consolidation, post-acquisition simplification or non-realised IPO plan - with supporting board minutes, financial projections and strategic memoranda. The Form RD-1 application packs this rationale clearly to address scrutiny upfront.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Newspaper publication and INC-26 service defects</td><td>The SINGLE most common reason for RD rejection is procedural defects in the newspaper publication or creditor notice service - wrong daily, partial publication, missed creditors, undocumented service.</td><td>Patron's Rule 41 procedure is followed precisely - English daily plus vernacular Hindi daily both circulating in Delhi, full INC-25A format, simultaneous publication, INC-26 individual service to every creditor and debenture holder with proof of dispatch, complete service documentation for the RD-1 application.</td></tr>

                    </tbody>
                </table>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

