            <h2 class="section-title" style="color:#FFFFFF !important;">Convert Your Public Ltd to Pvt Ltd in Delhi</h2>
            <div class="content-text" style="text-align:left;">
                
                <p style="color:rgba(255,255,255,0.9);">Conversion of a Public Limited Company to a Private Limited Company is the appropriate response when the original public structure was adopted for an IPO plan that did not materialise, when the family-controlled or closely-held company wants tighter promoter control and lighter governance, or when post-acquisition simplification by a strategic buyer is the driver. The procedural pathway is Section 14 of the Companies Act 2013 read with Rule 41 of the Companies (Incorporation) Rules 2014 - and the critical complication versus the reverse direction is the requirement for explicit Regional Director approval via Form RD-1, with mandatory newspaper publication of Form INC-25A, individual notice to all creditors and debenture holders in Form INC-26 and a 21-day objection window.</p>
                <p style="color:rgba(255,255,255,0.9);">The eligibility-side constraints are strict - member count under 200 (Section 2(68)), no outstanding public deposits, no ongoing investigation, inspection or prosecution under Rule 41(5) and for listed candidates, SEBI delisting under SEBI Regulations 2021 as a mandatory precondition. For growth-stage companies whose Public Limited status no longer justifies the heavier compliance load (statutory audit thresholds, secretarial audit, cost audit, AOC-4 XBRL, MGT-7, 4 quarterly board meetings, independent directors above thresholds, SEBI LODR if listed), the conversion is a one-time event that resets the compliance calendar to the lighter Private Limited schedule.</p>
                <p style="color:rgba(255,255,255,0.9);">Patron Accounting LLP runs the full Section 14 conversion from a Delhi office at INR 49,999 (Exl GST and Govt. Charges) - end-to-end with CA and CS named sign-off, direct Regional Director relationship at Lok Nayak Bhawan, Rule 41 procedure followed precisely and the post-conversion compliance calendar reset built in.</p>

            </div>
